name: 3,5-diphenyl-1h-pyrazole
Reason: 3,5-diphenyl-1H-pyrazole has a melting point that is influenced by several structural components. The basic unit for comparison is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of two additional phenyl rings. Phenyl groups, when connected to a benzene ring, tend to increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. In the case of 3,5-diphenyl-1H-pyrazole, we have two additional phenyl rings linked in a linear fashion, which would notably augment the melting point. Each additional phenyl group can be estimated to add approximately 100°C to the melting point due to increased pi-pi interactions, rigidity, and molecular weight. Additionally, the pyrazole ring introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions, raising the melting point by approximately +20°C.
